## The Bow-Tie Amplification Curve

Every oval cut diamond has a bow-tie effect — this is not optional and cannot be engineered away. The bow-tie is a dark shadow across the widest section of the stone caused by the facet arrangement that is inherent to the elongated elliptical outline.

What changes with L/W ratio is **severity**. Most guides treat bow-tie as a binary — either present or not. This is wrong. Bow-tie severity follows a curve that intensifies with elongation.

Here is that curve, based on observed Blue Nile inventory across hundreds of elongated ovals:

| L/W Ratio | Bow-Tie Severity | Buying Risk | Required Action |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1.45–1.50 | Minimal to light | Low | Standard video check |
| 1.50–1.55 | Light to moderate | Moderate | Careful video audit |
| 1.55–1.60 | Moderate | Moderate-High | Reject any stone where bow-tie blacks out in still frame |
| 1.60–1.65 | Moderate to strong | High | Video audit in multiple lighting conditions required |
| Over 1.65 | Strong to severe | Very High | Reject unless bow-tie is minimal on video |

The critical insight: **the GIA certificate cannot reveal bow-tie severity.** GIA grades oval cut diamonds as "Modified Brilliant" but does not assign a cut quality grade or bow-tie assessment. Two diamonds with identical GIA grades and identical L/W ratios can have dramatically different bow-tie severity depending on subtle variations in pavilion angle, culet depth, and facet arrangement.

The only way to evaluate bow-tie severity is to watch the 360° HD video of the specific stone. On Blue Nile's platform, every diamond listing includes this video. Watch the stone as it rotates. A healthy elongated oval will show a mild shadow at the center that lightens and shifts as the stone moves. A severe bow-tie will show a persistent dark stripe that remains dark across most of the stone's rotation.

> "The bow-tie in an elongated oval is not a flaw to avoid at all costs — it is a variable to manage. A minimal bow-tie in a well-proportioned 1.55 ratio stone is essentially invisible in ambient lighting and adds character to the stone's face. The problem is a moderate-to-severe bow-tie that can make a $15,000 stone look like it has a dirty windshield across its face. At L/W 1.60+, I reject more than half of the stones I review at first cut. Watch the video, watch the video, watch the video — three times, in three lighting conditions if possible." — **Farzana Hasan, [Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

---

## Which Settings Work Best for Elongated Oval Diamonds

Not all settings are equally effective for elongated ovals. The extreme tip geometry, the longer north-to-south dimension, and the bow-tie positioning all influence which settings work and which ones should be avoided.

### Solitaire Settings — The Default for Elongated Ovals

The solitaire is the most popular setting for elongated oval diamonds because it places no visual interruptions along the stone's length — the full north-to-south dimension is unobstructed. An elongated oval in a solitaire setting delivers the maximum finger-lengthening effect possible.

The six-prong solitaire is strongly preferred over four-prong for elongated ovals. With four prongs, two prongs sit at the north and south tips — but these prongs may not sit directly at the narrowest point of the tip on a highly elongated stone, leaving micro-sections of the tip exposed. With six prongs, two additional prongs sit mid-length on each side, creating a more complete encirclement that also adds side pressure against the elongated stone body.

