## Six Prongs vs. Four Prongs for Elongated Oval Diamond Rings

This question matters more for elongated ovals than for any other diamond shape. Here is the exact mechanical argument:

**The four-prong case:** Four prongs sit at the cardinal points — north, south, east, west — of the stone's outline. For a moderately elongated oval at L/W 1.50–1.52, the north and south prongs land close to the actual tips. The stone is reasonably protected and the four-prong look exposes maximum diamond surface for light entry.

**The six-prong case:** Six prongs sit at north, south, east, west, northeast, and southwest — six points distributed more evenly around the stone's perimeter. For elongated ovals at L/W 1.53+, the northeast and southwest prongs add a contact point on the elongated body that prevents micro-movement and rotational slippage. The north and south prongs sit exactly at the tips in most setting configurations.

**The practical rule:**
- L/W 1.50–1.52: Four prong is acceptable for low-activity wear. Six prong is better.
- L/W 1.53–1.60: Six prong is strongly recommended.
- L/W 1.61+: Six prong is mandatory. Bezel is better if protection is the primary concern.

The [Classic Six-Prong at $1,000](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-six-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-item-203272?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) with 1,894 reviews is the market's validation of this principle — it is the most-reviewed oval setting on Blue Nile by a factor of nearly three over the next competitor.

