## Metal Choice for Elongated Oval Diamond Rings

Metal choice affects two things in an elongated oval: the apparent color of the stone and the visual contrast with the elongated outline.

| Metal | Color Effect on Elongated Oval | Best Color Grade | Premium vs. 14K YG |
|---|---|---|---|
| 14K Yellow Gold | Warms G–H — hides any tip concentration | G–H | Baseline |
| 18K Yellow Gold | Richer gold tone, same color warming | G–H | +$300–$500 |
| 14K Rose Gold | Slight warmth — flattering to elongated outline | G–H | +$50–$100 |
| 14K White Gold | Color-neutral; requires rhodium every 2–3 years | F–G | +$100–$200 |
| Platinum | Most neutral; shows any body color | E–F | +$400–$800 |

**The elongated oval color rule:** Because an elongated oval concentrates slightly more body color at the tips (the farthest points from the center facets), a minimum G color in white gold or platinum is required. In yellow or rose gold, H color reads as near-colorless and saves $1,000–2,500 on a 2ct stone compared to buying G color.

**For L/W 1.60+ in yellow gold:** The warm gold tone fully neutralizes the elongated tips' color concentration. H color in 14K yellow gold at this ratio is visually identical to F color in platinum at a fraction of the price. This is one of the most significant cost optimizations available to elongated oval buyers.

