## Elongated vs. Classic Oval: The Face-Up Size Difference

One of the most overlooked advantages of an elongated oval is that it genuinely faces up larger than a classic oval of identical carat weight. This is not an optical illusion — it is a consequence of how carat weight distributes differently across the elongated outline.

When a diamond cutter produces a 1.60 L/W oval from a rough stone, they sacrifice some east-west width to achieve the elongated form. The result: the elongated oval has less "belly" depth (less weight hidden below the girdle) and more of its carat weight expressed in face-up surface area. A 2ct oval at 1.40 L/W measures approximately 10.5 × 7.5mm. The same 2ct oval at 1.60 L/W measures approximately 11.5 × 7.0mm. The elongated oval is 1mm longer north-to-south — which is the dimension that matters most on the finger.

For buyers comparing 1.5ct vs. 2ct: a 1.5ct elongated oval at L/W 1.60 delivers nearly identical north-to-south finger coverage as a 2ct classic oval at L/W 1.40 — at a $5,000–$8,000 lower stone price. This is the most concrete dollar argument for choosing an elongated oval over a classic one at the same budget.

| Stone | L/W | North-South Length | East-West Width | Finger Coverage |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 2ct oval | 1.40 | ~10.5mm | ~7.5mm | Standard coverage |
| **2ct oval** | **1.55** | **~11.0mm** | **~7.1mm** | **+0.5mm N-S coverage** |
| 2ct oval | 1.60 | ~11.5mm | ~7.0mm | +1.0mm N-S coverage |
| 1.5ct oval | 1.60 | ~10.5mm | ~6.5mm | Similar N-S to 2ct at 1.40 |

