## How to Buy an Elongated Oval Diamond Ring: Step-by-Step

**Step 1: Set your L/W target before you search.**
Decide whether you want moderate elongation (1.50–1.55), strong elongation (1.55–1.60), or dramatic elongation (1.60–1.65). This filters your diamond search before you see a single stone. Filter Blue Nile's oval diamond search by shape, then sort by carat weight and examine measurements to calculate L/W (divide length by width — both are shown in the measurements field).

**Step 2: Apply the color minimum for your metal.**
If buying yellow gold: G minimum for elongated ovals, H acceptable for L/W 1.50–1.55 only. If buying platinum or white gold: F minimum for L/W 1.55+, G minimum for 1.50–1.55.

**Step 3: Set clarity at VS1 minimum.**
VS1 guarantees eye-clean appearance in an elongated oval at any carat weight under 3ct. SI1 can be eye-clean in ovals but the inclusions must be evaluated individually — not recommended without video inspection. VS2 is acceptable if you are confident in the video audit.

**Step 4: Watch the 360° video for bow-tie severity.**
Apply the Bow-Tie Amplification Curve standards above. Reject any stone at L/W 1.60+ where the bow-tie blacks out completely in the 360° video, even in direct overhead lighting. A minimal bow-tie that shifts and lightens as the stone rotates is acceptable and expected.

**Step 5: Select a six-prong setting for L/W 1.53+.**
For L/W 1.50–1.52, a four-prong is acceptable. For anything above 1.52, use six prongs. The [Classic Six-Prong at $1,000](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-six-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-item-203272?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the default recommendation for all elongated oval buyers.

**Step 6: Choose metal for color and budget.**
Yellow gold: G–H color, maximum savings. White gold/platinum: F–G color, maximum color neutrality. See the metal guide above.

