## The East-West Elongated Oval: A Special Case

When an elongated oval is mounted horizontally — east-west orientation — the stone's behavior changes entirely. The elongated axis now runs east-west across the hand rather than north-south up the finger. This creates a wide, low-profile ring that emphasizes finger width rather than finger length.

For L/W ratios of 1.60–1.65, east-west mounting is particularly effective because the dramatic elongation becomes a horizontal sweep across the hand — visually bold and modern rather than the traditional vertical engagement ring look. The bow-tie, which runs across the stone's longest axis, now runs horizontally across the ring — some buyers find this less distracting in east-west orientation because the eye naturally reads the bow-tie as a band element rather than a stone defect.

See the [east-west oval diamond ring guide](/east-west-oval-diamond-ring) for all east-west specific settings and orientation guidelines.

