## Frequently Asked Questions

**What is an elongated oval diamond ring?**
An elongated oval diamond ring is a ring built around an oval diamond with a length-to-width (L/W) ratio of 1.50 or higher. The elongated oval delivers a more pronounced finger-lengthening effect than a classic oval (L/W 1.35–1.50) and is the most searched engagement ring style in {{year}}.

**What is the best length to width ratio for an elongated oval diamond?**
The ideal L/W ratio for an elongated oval is 1.55–1.60. This delivers a strongly elongated silhouette with a manageable bow-tie risk. Below 1.50, the effect is mild. Above 1.65, bow-tie severity increases significantly and the stone requires careful video auditing before purchase.

**What is the best oval diamond length to width ratio overall?**
For the classic oval look: 1.35–1.50. For the elongated look: 1.50–1.65. For a modern east-west or fashion-forward ring: 1.60–1.70. The GIA certificate lists the L/W ratio directly — no calculation required.

**Do elongated oval diamonds have a bigger bow-tie?**
Yes. Bow-tie shadow intensifies as L/W ratio increases. This is the Bow-Tie Amplification Curve described in this guide. At 1.50–1.55, the bow-tie is typically manageable. At 1.60–1.65, the bow-tie requires a careful video audit before purchase. At 1.65+, most stones will have a visible-to-strong bow-tie and must be evaluated individually.

**How many prongs should an elongated oval diamond ring have?**
Six prongs for any elongated oval at L/W 1.53 or higher. The six-prong setting places prongs at the stone's narrow tips — the most vulnerable points of an elongated oval. Four prongs are acceptable for L/W 1.50–1.52 only. A bezel setting provides the strongest protection for L/W 1.60+.

**What is a large oval diamond?**
In the context of elongated oval rings, "large" typically refers to stones of 2ct or above. At 2ct with L/W 1.55, the stone measures approximately 11.0 × 7.1mm — this is a visually commanding stone on any finger. At 3ct with L/W 1.55, the stone approaches 13.0 × 8.4mm — a trophy-class statement piece.

**Is an elongated oval diamond cheaper than a classic oval?**
Not directly — price is determined by carat weight, color, and clarity, not by L/W ratio. However, because elongated ovals face up larger than classic ovals at equal carat weight (more face-up surface per carat), a buyer targeting a specific visual size can achieve that look at a lower carat weight — and therefore lower price — with an elongated oval. A 1.5ct elongated oval at L/W 1.60 has similar north-to-south coverage to a 2ct classic oval at L/W 1.40.

**What color grade is best for an elongated oval diamond?**
G color minimum for white gold and platinum settings. H color is acceptable in 14K yellow gold or rose gold. Elongated ovals concentrate slightly more body color at the tips than classic ovals — a G color in platinum guarantees no visible warmth at the elongated tips. Going below H in yellow gold is not recommended for L/W 1.55+.

**How do I find elongated oval diamonds on Blue Nile?**
Search for oval diamonds on Blue Nile, then sort by the measurements field. Calculate L/W by dividing the listed length by the listed width (e.g., 10.50 ÷ 6.75 = 1.56). Filter stones to carat weight, color, and clarity targets, then manually review measurements for each stone to find those in the 1.50–1.65 range. Blue Nile does not have a direct L/W ratio filter — measurement calculation is the only method.

**Does an elongated oval diamond look bigger than a classic oval?**
Yes — at equal carat weight, an elongated oval has more north-to-south finger coverage than a classic oval. The stone covers more of the finger's vertical dimension. The east-west width is slightly narrower, but the net visual impression is a larger stone because human perception weights length more than width in a ring context.

**What setting hides the bow-tie in an elongated oval?**
No setting hides the bow-tie — it is a property of the stone, not the setting. The only solution is to select a stone with a minimal bow-tie. A bezel setting slightly reduces the impact because the metal rim around the perimeter draws attention away from the center, but a severe bow-tie is visible in a bezel regardless. Buy the stone based on video, not the setting.

**Should I buy a 2ct elongated oval or a 1.5ct elongated oval?**
For finger coverage, a [2ct elongated oval at L/W 1.55](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?Shape=Oval&Carats=2&Color=G&Clarity=VS2&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the optimal choice — it measures approximately 11.0mm north-to-south, which is visually striking on any finger. The [1.5ct elongated oval](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?Shape=Oval&Carats=1.5&Color=G&Clarity=VS2&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is more budget-friendly and still delivers a strong elongation effect. The key difference: the 2ct has more face-up presence across the width as well as length.

**What is the price difference between natural and lab-grown elongated oval diamonds?**
At 2ct G-VS2, a natural elongated oval costs approximately $17,480 on Blue Nile. A lab-grown 2ct G-VVS2 costs approximately $2,847 — a saving of over $14,600 for a stone with higher clarity. Lab-grown elongated ovals are optically and chemically identical to natural stones. The L/W ratio is equally available in lab-grown inventory.

